===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|pleyen}}, {{m|enm|playen}}, {{m|enm|pleȝen}}, {{m|enm|plæien}}, also {{inh|en|enm|plaȝen}}, {{m|enm|plawen}} {{gloss|compare English {{m|en|plaw}}}}, from {{inh|en|ang|pleġan}}, {{m|ang|pleoġan}}, {{m|ang|plæġan}}, and {{inh|en|ang|plegian}}, {{m|ang|pleagian}}, {{m|ang|plagian||to play, exercise, etc.}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*plehan||to care about, be concerned with}} and {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*plegōn||to engage, move}}; both perhaps from {{der|en|ine-pro|*blek-||to move, move about}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bal-}} (compare {{cog|grc|βλύω}}, {{m|grc|βλύζω||I gush out, spring}}, {{cog|sa|बल्बलीति||it whirls, twirls}}). Cognate with {{cog|sco|play||to act or move briskly, cause to move, stir}}, {{cog|stq|pleegje||to look after, care for, maintain}}, {{cog|fy|pleegje}}, {{m|fy|pliigje||to commit, perform, bedrive}}, {{cog|dum|pleyen}} {{gloss|"to dance, leap for joy, rejoice, be glad"; compare Modern {{cog|nl|pleien||to play a particular children's game}}}}, {{cog|nl|plegen||to commit, bedrive, practice}}, {{cog|de|pflegen||to care for, be concerned with, attend to, tend}}, {{cog|da|pleje||to tend to, nurse}}, {{cog|sv|pläga||to be wont to, be accustomed to}}. Related also to {{cog|ang|plēon||to risk, endanger}}. More at {{l|en|plight}}, {{l|en|pledge}}.

The noun is from {{inh|en|enm|pleye}}, from {{inh|en|ang|plæġ}}, {{m|ang|plega}}, {{m|ang|plæġa||play, quick motion, movement, exercise; (athletic) sport, game; festivity, drama; battle; gear for games, an implement for a game; clapping with the hands, applause}}, deverbative of {{m|ang|plegian||to play}}; see above.

